04:00.141 --> 04:01.849
My briefcase.

04:14.572 --> 04:15.521
Gotta fly.

04:15.781 --> 04:16.454
Don't worry.

04:16.480 --> 04:18.048
More people crash in cars.

04:18.284 --> 04:21.817
It's a lot safer to fly than crossing the street.

04:22.036 --> 04:24.326
If it's your time to go, it's your time to go.

04:24.748 --> 04:28.282
And remember, don't let your arms get tired!

04:28.793 --> 04:31.035
What if it's the pilot's time to go?

04:32.005 --> 04:33.476
Come on, keep us alive, Banning!

04:33.502 --> 04:34.237
Keep us alive!

04:34.425 --> 04:35.290
Okay, come on!

04:35.509 --> 04:36.600
Hi, Mrs. Banning.

04:36.626 --> 04:37.947
I'm from the office.

04:37.973 --> 04:39.448
Which one's your son?

04:39.679 --> 04:42.087
- He's up to bat!
- Thank you!

04:43.224 --> 04:44.600
Come on, Jack!

04:46.978 --> 04:48.887
Come on, pal!

04:49.105 --> 04:49.935
Come on, Jack!

04:50.523 --> 04:51.981
Don't look at me! Focus!

04:52.566 --> 04:54.227
Stay focused! Come on, Jack.

04:54.253 --> 04:55.261
One time, Jack.

04:56.779 --> 04:59.187
Come on, Jack! Come on, Jack!

05:00.741 --> 05:02.734
Please, not a curve ball.

05:03.119 --> 05:05.381
Mama wants a new pair of shoes.

05:05.407 --> 05:07.011
Drive me home, Jack!

05:12.627 --> 05:13.623
That's the game!

06:03.094 --> 06:04.753
Yeah, Brad, that's real good.

06:12.727 --> 06:15.598
<i>Good evening, ladies and gentlemen, your captain again.</i>

06:15.814 --> 06:19.479
<i>Please do not allow this minor turbulence to disturb you.</i>

06:29.494 --> 06:31.453
<i>For now, please sit back, relax.</i>

06:31.479 --> 06:33.682
<i>Enjoy the remainder of the flight.</i>

06:33.873 --> 06:35.118
<i>Thank you.</i>

06:36.000 --> 06:37.826
Look what Jack drew!

06:38.043 --> 06:39.621
That's very nice, dear.

06:39.837 --> 06:40.952
What's that?

06:41.506 --> 06:42.336
Fire.

06:42.548 --> 06:44.422
Fire! Really?

06:44.675 --> 06:46.170
Is that our plane?

06:47.720 --> 06:48.834
Who are these people?

06:49.054 --> 06:52.637
That's Jack, that's me, that's Mom...

06:52.891 --> 06:54.516
...and that's you.

06:55.477 --> 06:56.675
Where's my parachute?

06:59.231 --> 07:00.944
I won't make it to my birthday.

07:00.970 --> 07:02.957
You won't die without a phone.

07:03.152 --> 07:04.978
I got the phone in the briefcase.

07:05.237 --> 07:06.517
Talk to him.

07:13.703 --> 07:15.577
Why didn't I have a parachute, Jackie?

07:15.997 --> 07:17.277
Take a wild guess.

07:17.540 --> 07:19.947
- Jackie!
- Jack.

07:20.293 --> 07:22.203
Will you stop?
You can break a window.

07:22.421 --> 07:23.272
They're layered.

07:23.298 --> 07:24.521
You can't break them.

07:24.839 --> 07:26.417
Give me that.

07:29.677 --> 07:31.551
You're afraid you'll get sucked out.

07:31.762 --> 07:33.043
I'm not afraid.

07:33.264 --> 07:33.902
Yes, you are.

07:33.928 --> 07:35.744
You're afraid you'll be sucked out.

07:35.975 --> 07:37.469
Just stop.

07:41.313 --> 07:44.184
Jack, next season, I'm coming to six games. I promise.

07:44.817 --> 07:47.687
Yeah, be sure to buy enough videotape.

07:52.741 --> 07:54.366
My word is my bond.

07:54.743 --> 07:56.403
Yeah, junk bond!

07:59.205 --> 08:02.289
When are you gonna stop acting like a child?

08:03.584 --> 08:04.617
I am a child.

08:04.837 --> 08:06.035
Grow up.

08:08.381 --> 08:09.840
<i>It's been a long time.</i>

08:10.091 --> 08:11.716
<i>Let's have fun, Peter.</i>

08:12.010 --> 08:13.967
London's a magical place for children.

08:14.179 --> 08:15.922
- It was for us.
- And expensive.

08:16.139 --> 08:17.189
Jack, don't do that.

08:17.215 --> 08:18.999
You could put someone's eye out.

08:19.267 --> 08:21.010
Maggie. Maggie.

08:21.227 --> 08:23.100
Peter, it's number 14.

08:23.312 --> 08:24.225
Sorry.

08:24.480 --> 08:26.272
What do you say to Granny Wendy?

08:26.524 --> 08:27.557
- "How do you do?"

08:27.583 --> 08:28.672
- Jack, get down!

08:28.860 --> 08:29.891
Be careful.

08:30.444 --> 08:33.563
Is Granny Wendy the real, real Wendy from my play?

08:33.823 --> 08:34.818
No, not really.

08:35.032 --> 08:36.491
Sort of.

08:36.866 --> 08:38.101
Don't be a sloucher.

08:38.126 --> 08:40.225
Take that gum out of your mouth.

08:40.453 --> 08:41.888
It's time to look our best.

08:41.914 --> 08:44.144
First impressions are the most important.

08:44.374 --> 08:46.284
Shoes tied. Shirt tucked.

08:46.502 --> 08:47.747
You know this.

08:49.254 --> 08:51.710
Remember, you're in England, land of good manners.

08:51.965 --> 08:52.795
Uncle Tootles.

08:53.008 --> 08:54.835
It's snowing!

09:05.895 --> 09:08.565
Look at these adorable children!

09:08.773 --> 09:11.145
It's good to see you, Libby... Linda... Lisa...

09:11.401 --> 09:13.393
- Liza.
- I said that.

09:14.195 --> 09:15.739
Oh, Moira, how are you?

09:15.765 --> 09:17.174
You look wonderful!

09:17.406 --> 09:18.865
Oh, my God!

09:19.075 --> 09:19.940
Look at the size...

09:20.159 --> 09:22.317
Look at you! Such a sweet thing!

09:22.536 --> 09:24.229
Granny Wendy will be right down.

09:24.255 --> 09:25.894
She's upstairs? Oh, good.

09:26.748 --> 09:30.200
- Big boy! You could play rugby.
- No, baseball.

09:30.544 --> 09:31.374
Oh, look.

09:31.587 --> 09:32.697
Did you do this for us?

09:32.723 --> 09:34.364
We've been cooking all week.

09:34.548 --> 09:35.718
You've been cooking?

09:35.744 --> 09:38.024
What've you been cooking?
Mince pies?

09:38.302 --> 09:40.377
Peter, look at this.
Look at this.

09:40.595 --> 09:42.422
- Who's that?
- It's you.

09:42.639 --> 09:44.631
Was I ever that young?

09:44.849 --> 09:46.295
What's gotten into you?

09:46.321 --> 09:48.457
This house has gotten to me.

09:48.686 --> 09:52.020
Some of those things I was when I was young have never left me.

09:52.274 --> 09:53.052
Oh, thank God!

09:53.078 --> 09:54.968
We were children in these rooms.

09:55.193 --> 09:57.980
Lost, lost, lost.

09:58.196 --> 09:59.476
Lost what?

10:00.323 --> 10:02.399
I've lost my marbles.

10:04.577 --> 10:05.822
Lisa?

10:06.662 --> 10:07.611
Liza.

10:07.830 --> 10:09.360
He was supposed to be in a home.

10:09.386 --> 10:10.773
It broke Wendy's heart.

10:10.959 --> 10:12.400
Tootles is Wendy's first orphan.

10:12.426 --> 10:13.190
Which is which?

10:13.378 --> 10:16.414
Large bag's mine, and the smaller ones are the children's.

10:16.672 --> 10:18.332
Hello, boy.

10:27.516 --> 10:29.259
Hello, Wendy.

10:38.151 --> 10:41.602
I told you, Gran, I'd get him here, by hook or by crook.

10:46.617 --> 10:48.693
I'm sorry it's been so long between visits.

10:48.953 --> 10:51.365
It's been 10 years between visits.

10:51.391 --> 10:52.597
But never mind.

10:52.833 --> 10:55.205
Come and give me a skwoodge.

11:02.550 --> 11:04.957
Oh, Moira, Moira, Moira!

11:07.137 --> 11:08.631
Who is this lovely lady?

11:08.889 --> 11:10.217
It can't be Maggie.

11:10.474 --> 11:12.306
Yes, it can.
And know what?

11:12.332 --> 11:14.367
I just played you at school.

11:14.562 --> 11:16.471
And don't you just look the part.

11:16.731 --> 11:18.324
Can this giant be Jack?

11:18.350 --> 11:20.705
How much you've grown in a year!

11:20.901 --> 11:22.728
I'm supposed to tell you about...

11:22.945 --> 11:27.072
...congratulations for opening the orphan hospital...

11:27.282 --> 11:30.615
...and how great the dedication is.

11:31.661 --> 11:34.497
- Thank you so very much.
- Welcome.

11:34.748 --> 11:39.374
Now, there is one rule I insist be obeyed while you are in my house:

11:40.045 --> 11:42.500
No growing up.

11:43.339 --> 11:46.091
Stop this very instant.

11:46.342 --> 11:49.426
And that includes you, Mr. Chairman-of-the-Board Banning.

11:49.679 --> 11:50.841
Sorry, too late, Gran.

11:51.055 --> 11:55.349
And what's so terribly important about your terribly important business?

11:55.602 --> 11:58.175
You see, when a big company's in trouble...

11:58.438 --> 12:01.273
...Dad sails in, and if there's any resistance...

12:01.524 --> 12:02.414
He's exaggerating.

12:02.440 --> 12:04.466
I'm still into mergers and acquisitions.

12:04.693 --> 12:07.184
And I'm dabbling in some land development.

12:07.404 --> 12:10.488
Any resistance and he blows them out of the water.

12:14.035 --> 12:15.578
So!

12:16.330 --> 12:19.414
Peter, you've become a pirate!

13:25.146 --> 13:26.476
Brad's on the line.

13:26.502 --> 13:28.042
He says it's urgent!

13:34.613 --> 13:35.811
Do you like my dress?

13:36.031 --> 13:37.656
Great, Gran.

13:39.118 --> 13:40.364
Thanks.

13:41.746 --> 13:44.284
Hey, Brad. Good news?

13:45.291 --> 13:46.536
What?

13:47.335 --> 13:48.668
What Sierra Club report?

13:48.694 --> 13:50.360
I thought we had these guys.

13:51.880 --> 13:53.713
He's trying to suck my blood!

13:53.739 --> 13:55.570
He drools all over my neck.

13:55.759 --> 13:56.790
What did they find?

13:57.010 --> 13:58.700
That's a portable phone...

13:58.726 --> 14:00.155
A Cozy Blue Owl?

14:01.640 --> 14:04.807
Well, listen.

14:05.018 --> 14:08.601
Ask them if anybody misses the Tyrannosaurus Rex.

14:08.855 --> 14:11.466
Oh, well, I do! Boy, do I ever!

14:11.492 --> 14:13.091
Wow, you kidding?

14:13.359 --> 14:14.273
Wait a minute.

14:14.486 --> 14:18.483
You telling me a 10-inch owl has a 50-mile mating radius?

14:18.698 --> 14:21.569
Why don't they just fornicate someplace else?

14:21.785 --> 14:26.612
You're telling me a 5-billion-dollar deal is falling apart because of this?

14:27.498 --> 14:29.206
Somebody shoot me in the head!

14:30.042 --> 14:31.240
Bang! Bang!

14:31.502 --> 14:32.913
Will everybody just shut up!

14:33.379 --> 14:34.209
I'm sorry.

14:34.630 --> 14:36.208
Leave me alone for one moment!

14:36.423 --> 14:37.517
Get them out of here!

14:37.543 --> 14:39.366
I'm on the phone call of my life!

14:40.719 --> 14:41.664
Come on, Jack.

14:41.690 --> 14:42.702
Out, out, out.

14:44.098 --> 14:45.592
Come with me.

14:45.891 --> 14:50.802
I'll show you the window where your dad and I used to blow out the stars.

14:53.357 --> 14:55.645
I should've stayed till the deal was done.

14:55.901 --> 14:58.356
Granny asked you to visit every year.

14:58.611 --> 14:59.560
I've been busy.

14:59.821 --> 15:02.539
You promised the children some real time here.

15:02.565 --> 15:04.473
You haven't looked at them once.

15:04.660 --> 15:05.594
That's not true.

15:05.620 --> 15:07.721
How many more broken promises?

15:13.918 --> 15:14.945
It's Brad, Moira.

15:14.971 --> 15:16.481
I gotta take this call.

15:17.380 --> 15:18.660
I gotta fix this.

15:19.215 --> 15:21.753
No, you gotta fix your family first.

15:30.059 --> 15:31.637
<i>Peter, hello?
Are you there?</i>

15:37.357 --> 15:38.602
What?

15:40.610 --> 15:42.013
I'm sorry about your deal.

15:42.039 --> 15:43.387
You hated the deal.

15:43.572 --> 15:44.710
I hated the deal.

15:44.736 --> 15:47.547
But I'm sorry you feel so badly about it.

15:48.452 --> 15:50.444
Your children love you.

15:50.913 --> 15:52.739
They want to play with you.

15:53.415 --> 15:55.657
How long do you think that lasts?

15:56.543 --> 15:59.828
Soon Jack may not even want you to come to his games.

16:01.172 --> 16:04.422
We have a few special years with our children...

16:04.634 --> 16:07.339
...when they're the ones that want us around.

16:07.846 --> 16:11.096
Then you'll be running after them for a bit of attention.

16:12.225 --> 16:14.217
It's so fast, Peter.

16:15.103 --> 16:18.388
It's a few years, then it's over.

16:21.609 --> 16:24.230
And you are not being careful.

16:26.196 --> 16:28.605
And you are missing it.

16:35.539 --> 16:37.163
<i>Peter, where are you?</i>

16:41.545 --> 16:44.462
<i>Peter! Peter! Peter!</i>

16:45.173 --> 16:49.670
"All children, except one, grow up."

16:50.470 --> 16:53.839
Now, you know where faeries come from, don't you, Maggie?

16:54.558 --> 16:58.472
"When the first baby laughed for the first time...

16:58.728 --> 17:01.598
...the laugh broke into a thousand pieces...

17:01.856 --> 17:03.979
...and they all went skipping about.

17:04.233 --> 17:06.605
That was the beginning of faeries."

17:06.861 --> 17:07.809
And look.

17:10.406 --> 17:12.198
I'm Wendy.

17:13.534 --> 17:15.942
Or was, a long time ago.

17:16.871 --> 17:20.570
But Jack says you're not the really "real" Wendy.

17:20.790 --> 17:22.829
Do you see where Jack is?

17:24.544 --> 17:26.037
Well, that's the same window.

17:26.063 --> 17:27.606
And this is the same room...

17:27.797 --> 17:32.460
...where we made up stories about Peter, Never Land and scary old Captain Hook.

17:32.720 --> 17:36.634
And do you know, Mr. Barrie, well, Sir James, our neighbor...

17:36.890 --> 17:40.970
...loved our stories so much that he wrote them all down in a book.

17:41.227 --> 17:44.181
Oh, dear me, 80 years ago.

17:44.772 --> 17:46.729
You're really old!

17:46.983 --> 17:48.892
That's very true.

17:49.860 --> 17:51.338
I'm sorry to break this up.

17:51.364 --> 17:52.840
I have to steal Granny...

17:53.031 --> 17:56.400
...or she'll be late for the most important event of her life.

18:00.246 --> 18:01.574
Oh, dear.

18:01.789 --> 18:03.707
Daddy, I made something for you.

18:03.733 --> 18:05.230
You're gonna love this.

18:05.459 --> 18:06.159
It's a hug.

18:06.185 --> 18:08.983
Next time you fly, you won't have to be scared.

18:09.213 --> 18:11.419
She's made you a parachute.

18:11.798 --> 18:13.922
That's very clever, dear.

18:15.386 --> 18:16.382
Get away from there!

18:16.595 --> 18:20.098
What have I told you about playing near open windows?

18:20.124 --> 18:21.745
Keep this window closed.

18:21.975 --> 18:23.517
Do we have open windows at home?

18:23.769 --> 18:26.010
No. They've all got bars on them.

18:26.479 --> 18:27.890
Come on. Into bed.

18:31.859 --> 18:33.189
Who took my baseball?

18:33.570 --> 18:36.904
That mean, scary man at the window stole it.

18:37.157 --> 18:38.320
There's no scary man.

18:38.575 --> 18:41.576
But he says he's a window washer.

18:43.371 --> 18:44.201
What's this?

18:44.455 --> 18:45.403
A baseball glove.

18:45.429 --> 18:47.267
You can catch things with it...

18:47.458 --> 18:50.791
...take hot things out of the oven, hit your sister with it.

18:52.463 --> 18:54.524
Tootles made it for me.

18:54.550 --> 18:56.071
It smells nice.

18:56.259 --> 18:57.718
It's paper, honey.

19:03.849 --> 19:05.427
Hey, Jack.

19:06.352 --> 19:07.727
Faker.

19:09.354 --> 19:11.394
You're in charge now.

19:11.606 --> 19:15.439
This is my very special watch, so you can keep track of the time.

19:15.736 --> 19:18.571
Don't go out, Mom. Please.

19:23.243 --> 19:24.618
Good night.

19:32.794 --> 19:36.662
Dear night-lights, protect my sleeping babes.

19:36.882 --> 19:40.665
Burn clear and steadfast tonight.

19:44.097 --> 19:49.221
I read recently that they're now using lawyers instead of rats for experiments.

19:50.144 --> 19:51.555
They do this for two reasons:

19:51.812 --> 19:56.106
One, the scientists become less attached to the lawyers.

19:57.026 --> 20:00.893
And two, there are certain things that even rats won't do.

20:06.743 --> 20:10.278
I thank the Board of Trustees of the Ormond Street Hospital...

20:10.539 --> 20:12.578
...for having me here this evening...

20:13.166 --> 20:17.578
...and beg your forgiveness because normally I address shareholders.

20:19.506 --> 20:24.251
We don't know each other, and I doubt that we have very much in common...

20:24.719 --> 20:28.633
...except this wonderful woman, Wendy Angela Darling.

20:31.434 --> 20:33.510
Granny Wendy brought me in from the cold.

20:33.728 --> 20:35.934
She taught me to read and write.

20:36.147 --> 20:39.232
She even found people to be my parents and adopt me.

20:41.152 --> 20:43.026
She's loved so many children...

20:43.237 --> 20:47.698
...just so efforlete...
efforse... effortlessly.

20:48.284 --> 20:49.908
That's her achievement.

20:50.411 --> 20:53.198
Many of you here tonight were once lost children...

20:53.413 --> 20:57.031
...but Granny Wendy found parents and homes for each of you...

20:57.292 --> 20:58.572
...and saved you.

20:58.835 --> 20:59.832
That's her miracle.

21:01.046 --> 21:05.589
I know that if you could stand now, you would express much better than I have...

21:05.843 --> 21:09.710
...your feelings of gratitude...

21:12.515 --> 21:14.093
...appreciation...

21:16.185 --> 21:18.059
...and warm feelings...

21:18.896 --> 21:20.771
...for this wonderful woman.

21:36.497 --> 21:39.118
I guess we do have something in common.

21:41.460 --> 21:43.085
We're orphans.

22:02.773 --> 22:04.765
Hook!

22:06.651 --> 22:08.110
Hook.

22:43.103 --> 22:44.383
Jack...

23:25.352 --> 23:26.728
You all right?

23:27.021 --> 23:28.266
Wendy?

23:45.079 --> 23:46.538
Thank you, Nigel. Norman?

23:46.789 --> 23:47.905
Neville, sir.

23:48.167 --> 23:49.661
Is that English?

23:49.960 --> 23:51.751
Merry Christmas.

23:54.047 --> 23:55.506
I was proud of you.

23:55.715 --> 23:57.921
It was a beautiful speech.

23:58.176 --> 23:59.884
Yes, it was.

24:19.572 --> 24:20.947
Liza?

24:21.323 --> 24:22.817
Tootles?

24:27.495 --> 24:30.118
My God!
The children!

24:37.047 --> 24:38.874
Jack! Answer me!

24:39.132 --> 24:40.377
Maggie!

24:41.801 --> 24:43.218
The wind came up.

24:43.244 --> 24:45.409
The door closed on me...

24:45.638 --> 24:47.880
...and the children were screaming!

24:48.140 --> 24:51.427
The children were screaming!

25:01.696 --> 25:02.941
The window.

25:16.293 --> 25:17.242
"Dear Peter:

25:17.461 --> 25:20.794
Your presence is required at the request of your children.

25:23.050 --> 25:25.375
Kindest personal regards...

25:25.594 --> 25:27.253
...J.A.S. Hook...

25:27.846 --> 25:29.126
...Captain."

25:34.228 --> 25:37.477
Have to fly. Have to fight.

25:37.856 --> 25:40.373
Have to crow. Have to save Maggie.

25:40.399 --> 25:41.878
Have to save Jack.

25:43.194 --> 25:45.068
Hook is back.

25:46.322 --> 25:47.353
Who?

25:48.741 --> 25:49.986
Gran!

25:55.623 --> 25:58.328
Well, the lab boys can analyze this little lot.

25:59.001 --> 26:03.959
We've wired the phones, and two of my lads will be outside at all times.

26:04.423 --> 26:08.123
It's possible that this is some kind of ridiculous prank.

26:08.385 --> 26:10.212
My children are missing.

26:10.721 --> 26:14.589
Yes, but the literary history of the family suggests...

26:14.892 --> 26:15.841
Let's hope...

26:16.060 --> 26:18.136
I've forgotten how to fly.

26:18.979 --> 26:21.268
Yeah, well, one does.

26:21.857 --> 26:22.812
Good night, ma'am.

26:22.838 --> 26:23.791
Good night, sir.

26:26.778 --> 26:29.613
No more happy thoughts.

26:30.823 --> 26:32.068
Lost!

26:33.367 --> 26:34.696
Lost!

26:46.881 --> 26:49.304
The police will do everything they can.

26:49.330 --> 26:51.318
The police can do nothing.

26:51.677 --> 26:54.880
Really? Maybe we should call the American police.

26:55.097 --> 26:57.719
In a crisis, we English always make a cup of tea.

26:57.934 --> 26:59.048
Moira, would you?

26:59.310 --> 27:00.259
Yes, of course.

27:00.478 --> 27:02.766
Don't forget to warm the pot.

27:04.023 --> 27:05.481
I'll go.

27:06.525 --> 27:07.984
You stay.

27:08.694 --> 27:11.694
Don't worry, Gran Wendy, I wasn't gonna leave.

27:12.864 --> 27:15.485
Hand me my book, please.

27:21.415 --> 27:23.621
It's time to tell you, at last.

27:25.335 --> 27:26.746
Tell me what?

27:27.879 --> 27:31.746
How far back can you remember, Peter?

27:32.967 --> 27:35.921
I remember the hospital on Great Ormond Street.

27:36.637 --> 27:38.262
You worked with orphans.

27:38.515 --> 27:41.966
You arranged for the adoption by my American parents.

27:42.560 --> 27:44.802
You were 12, nearly 13.

27:45.062 --> 27:46.971
I mean, before that.

27:47.440 --> 27:49.099
There's nothing before that.

27:50.734 --> 27:53.023
Try, Peter. Do try.

27:54.988 --> 27:56.363
Nothing.

28:00.619 --> 28:03.655
You know, when I was young...

28:05.999 --> 28:09.285
...no other girl held your favor the way I did.

28:11.546 --> 28:16.671
I expected you to alight on the church and forbid my vows on my wedding day.

28:17.844 --> 28:20.762
I wore a pink satin sash.

28:23.516 --> 28:25.343
But you didn't come.

28:26.895 --> 28:28.270
Grandma?

28:29.355 --> 28:33.399
Yes, I was an old lady when I wrapped you in blankets.

28:33.651 --> 28:35.394
A grandmother.

28:35.653 --> 28:38.404
With my 13-year-old granddaughter asleep in the bed.

28:38.655 --> 28:39.900
Moira.

28:40.741 --> 28:42.651
And when you saw her...

28:43.744 --> 28:47.327
...that was when you decided not to go back to Never Land.

28:49.833 --> 28:50.996
Where?

28:51.585 --> 28:53.708
To Never Never Land.

28:56.089 --> 28:56.820
I'll get Moira.

28:56.846 --> 28:58.356
I've tried to tell you...

28:58.550 --> 28:59.716
Maybe the tea's ready.

28:59.742 --> 29:01.279
I knew you'd forgotten!

29:01.469 --> 29:03.427
I'm not ready to deal with this now.

29:03.639 --> 29:05.880
The stories are true.

29:05.906 --> 29:07.613
I swear to you.

29:08.351 --> 29:10.558
I swear on everything I adore.

29:10.770 --> 29:13.771
And now he's come back to seek his revenge.

29:14.023 --> 29:16.561
The fight isn't over for Captain James Hook.

29:16.776 --> 29:17.725
He wants you back.

29:17.944 --> 29:21.526
He knows you'll follow Maggie and Jack to the ends of the earth.

29:21.739 --> 29:24.990
And, by heaven, you must find a way.

29:26.119 --> 29:29.570
Only you can save your children.

29:30.915 --> 29:33.750
Somehow, you must go back.

29:34.877 --> 29:38.127
You must make yourself remember.

29:39.881 --> 29:41.673
Remember what?

29:43.968 --> 29:47.504
Peter, don't you know who you are?

30:08.827 --> 30:10.237
Yes, boy.

30:11.913 --> 30:13.158
Yes.

